review_text: Dickinson Square Park is a historic and vibrant green space located in the Pennsport neighborhood of South Philadelphia. Named after John Dickinson, a Founding Father of the United States, the park occupies an entire city block between 4th & 3rd Street / Tasker & Morris Street. It‚Äôs a place where community members gather to enjoy basketball courts, swing sets, jungle gym equipment, and the shade of large trees spread across its 3 acres. The park stands on the site of the former Pascal Iron Works and was transformed into a public park that opened in 1900. Today, Dickinson Square Park continues to serve as a safe, comfortable, and pleasing open space in a densely populated area, hosting an outdoor, producer-only farmers‚Äô market and various community events.

I've biked here a couple times from Center City with my husband and some friends. It's a nice park, especially for kids with the giant playground and the basketball court. There's plenty of space to spread out a blanket, but unfortunately today we realized the trees do a lot of sap dripping this time of year. It felt like a light spritz of rain every now and again to sit under a tree. We were back behind the basketball court, if that matters. No public restrooms it seemed - there is some kind of building in the center but it didn't appear to have bathrooms. Thought that was odd considering all the families who held birthday parties there but perhaps someone lived close by and the families just used their bathrooms. There also aren't too many places to lock up a bike that we noticed.

If you get hungry and need some food for your picnic, Gooey Looie's close by has amazing sandwiches (cash only, but there is an ATM there).

This neighborhood park is a hidden gem in South Philly just a short walk south from Washington Avenue to Moyamensing. We visted with our dog on a weekend and every part of the block-sized park was in use. Kids were on the playground, lots of leashed dogs exercising, families hanging out on the grass and benches. There's a stunning block-long Mural Arts mural across the street. There were community garden beds waiting to be planted in the spring. I don't know if the castle-like building is open to the public.The park grounds were well-maintained and everything was in good repair. We've heard that the Mummers do concerts here seasonally, and will have to come back.
